<div id="review_470556347" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/470556347" />
    <a title="Jason" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2447803-jason"><img alt="Jason" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1246308632p2/2447803.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/470556347?book_show_action=true">Dec 05, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jason" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jason" href="/user/show/2447803-jason">Jason</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780671211325" href="/book/show/936815.Zorba_the_Greek">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer470556347" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10723199083141662663">Don’t read this book either. I nabbed it at the library because of the first 2 sentences. I lived on Crete, Greece for a year, on the rural bluffs over Kalathas Beach on the island’s northwest spine. I was hoping to reminisce about the countryside, the pebble beaches, the goats, the nudity, the olive and grape fields, the odors, and the blooming bougainvillea that climbed the outdoor plumbing and entered my second story bathroom window.<br/><br/>I wanted to be your expert and validate the setting of <i>Zorba</i></span>
  <span id="freeText10723199083141662663" style="display:none">Don’t read this book either. I nabbed it at the library because of the first 2 sentences. I lived on Crete, Greece for a year, on the rural bluffs over Kalathas Beach on the island’s northwest spine. I was hoping to reminisce about the countryside, the pebble beaches, the goats, the nudity, the olive and grape fields, the odors, and the blooming bougainvillea that climbed the outdoor plumbing and entered my second story bathroom window.<br /><br />I wanted to be your expert and validate the setting of <i>Zorba the Greek</i>, which, except for more internal combustion engines today, should be unchanged since it was written in the 1940’s. Instead the book was written to capture the spirit and culture of the people, not to document the environs. I was nostalgic for the beauty of the dry, mountainous island at the foot of Greece and the darkened nipples of topless sunbathers. So there’s no Samaria Gorge, no Eliphanesis Beach, no cobalt blue of the Libyan Sea, no Palace of Knossos, no beach caves of Matala, no shallow Roman-era harbors of Rethymno or Chania. <br /><br />I would live again in Crete. No wi-fi, no Western news cycle, no problem.<br /><br /><i>Zorba the Greek</i> is the oft-repeated story of 2 men at odds about how to fully enjoy and experience life. Zorba lives by action; the narrator lives by study and writing (a thinly veiled biographic for Kazantzakis himself?). Isolated together for several months in a small town on Crete, we see the juxtaposition. The allegory is not overly heavy-handed, but it’s apparent from the outset and lacks discriminating subtlety. The narrator begins to revere Zorba, this little dancing man, and by the end has somewhat incorporated his worldview, and leaves the reader to believe he will adopt the zany spontaneity and overly machismo characteristics Zorba exhibits like a male bird in the bough.<br /> <br />These manly stories of vicarious self discovery are better written by the Russians.<br /><br />The only thing I found downright distasteful about the story is a tenor of misogyny throughout, a sure product of the caucasian, Mediterranean male (something that also hasn’t changed since the ‘40s). Women are objects to sleep with and figures that prepare food. Whatever, it's periodic writing. It's a forgettable story.<br /><br />Read <i>Zorba</i> if it’s the only book available and you’re laid over in Cincinnati for a Christmas Nor'easter, waiting for a break in weather at a mid-Atlantic city.<br /> <br />No outstanding sentences, but I did learn a new word: <i>bey</i>.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10723199083141662663" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


