<div id="review_3276503957" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3276503957" />
    <a title="Prickle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57115665-prickle"><img alt="Prickle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1528206407p2/57115665.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3276503957?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Prickle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Prickle" href="/user/show/57115665-prickle">Prickle</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781476782812" href="/book/show/22716193-zorba-the-greek">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3276503957" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11153631014110909560">Or by its intentionally thinly disguised alternate title: <i>Zarathustra the Dancer</i>. <br/><br/>One asks if everything Hermann Hesse wrote was wrong-headed after all when Kazantzakis writes this on such lithe feet and still leaves time to give the Buddha himself such a clowning and slap on the other cheek that one wonders if he wasn&apos;t some fable made up to scare children with. And incredibly, he does the same across the gamut of ideologies from Christianity to nationalism in this book without seeming inwardly</span>
  <span id="freeText11153631014110909560" style="display:none">Or by its intentionally thinly disguised alternate title: <i>Zarathustra the Dancer</i>. <br /><br />One asks if everything Hermann Hesse wrote was wrong-headed after all when Kazantzakis writes this on such lithe feet and still leaves time to give the Buddha himself such a clowning and slap on the other cheek that one wonders if he wasn't some fable made up to scare children with. And incredibly, he does the same across the gamut of ideologies from Christianity to nationalism in this book without seeming inwardly spiteful of any of them at all. <br /><br />What a character it must have taken to have been in Greece in WWII and to leave THIS book as the result. And if the Anglo-sphere has gradually forgotten Kazantzakis with time, with just a cursory glance at the Goodreads reviews it seems the mediterranean and middle-East definitely have not, though chilled Northerners in particular would especially benefit from this book. Despite its overtly Nietzschean and Bergsonian core it reminds me much of the Bible, of Don Quixote, of works in the oral tradition with Leskov as easily a third of the book are the immensely poignant anecdotes and vignettes delivered by characters themselves, of Homer of course, and strangely even of The Magic Mountain, but whereas Mann always rounds off every sentence with a polish Kazantzakis doesn't mince words, and doesn't pull back even when something hits overly sentimental or crude to us jaded moderns; it moves constantly at its own rhythm, and is certainly not afraid to deliver harsh words to the reader like an attack on our senses and sedate way of life behind every paragraph. Zorba even encourages a renegade monk to burn down a Greek monastery and gives him a shave afterwards so he looks like a Catholic. But even so, every chapter literally dances with joy.<br /><br />I wrote a much lengthier review and deleted it, as this work certainly doesn't need it. Suffice it to say I liked this book very much. Here's something of one of the vignettes I mentioned, see if it's to your rhythm and palette:<br /><br /><i>"When the royal steamship arrived all decorated with flags and the cannonade began and Prince George trod Cretan soil, have you ever seen an entire population driven mad all together because they've seen their freedom?... If each person were allowed to pick his own heavenly Paradise according to his taste (that's how it should be; that's the meaning of Paradise), I would say to God: 'Dear God, let my Paradise be a Crete filled with myrtles and flags, and let the moment when Prince George treads Cretan soil last for eternities. That's all I want."<br /><br />"What happened in Crete, Zorba? Keep talking!"<br /><br />"Are we going to keep on saying words? Look here, what I'm telling you is that this world is a mystery and every human being is a great brute—a great brute and a great god. A wicked partisan named Yiorgharos had come down with me from Macedonia, a criminal who'd done unbelievable things, a filthy pig—and he was weeping. 'What are you bawling about, Yiorgharos? Why are you boo-hooing, you pig?' I ask him, my own eyes having turned on the waterworks. But he falls all over me and, yes, starts kissing me and sobbing like a babe in arms. Then this miserly skinflint undoes his leather money belt, empties out into his lap the golden pounds he plundered from the Turks he killed and the homes he violated, and tosses them into the air, handful after handful. Do you understand, Boss? That's what freedom means!"</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="11153631014110909560" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


