    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_947244211" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/947244211" />
    <a title="Czarny Pies" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies"><img alt="Czarny Pies" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400687408p2/29160274.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/947244211?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Czarny Pies" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Czarny Pies" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies">Czarny Pies</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29160274-czarny-pies?shelf=southern-slav-greek-lit">southern-slav-greek-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer947244211" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9806400529626154554">This is a sad story set in sunny Crete. Our narrator hero is an intellectual and a socialist. He reads Dante, attempts to practice Boudhism and re-opens an abandoned mine to provide employment for the workers on the island.<br/><br/>He becomes friends with the older Zorba, an unschooled child of nature, who spends most of the novel debating deep philosophical issues with the narrator.<br/><br/>Zorba and the narrator begin what looks like an idyll on the island paradise. They watch a tragedy unfold before their eyes</span>
  <span id="freeText9806400529626154554" style="display:none">This is a sad story set in sunny Crete. Our narrator hero is an intellectual and a socialist. He reads Dante, attempts to practice Boudhism and re-opens an abandoned mine to provide employment for the workers on the island.<br /><br />He becomes friends with the older Zorba, an unschooled child of nature, who spends most of the novel debating deep philosophical issues with the narrator.<br /><br />Zorba and the narrator begin what looks like an idyll on the island paradise. They watch a tragedy unfold before their eyes. A young boy becomes infatuated with a beautiful widow. When taunted about his infatuation, he commits suicide and the father kills the widow in rage. The working class it appears is filled with men of brutal, primitive instincts. <br /><br />Under his incompetent management, the narrator's mine fails. The narrator departs the island glad to have developed a fast friendship with the noble-savage philosopher.<br /><br />Somehow this preposterous novel is converted into great fun by the film of the same name featuring Anthony Quinn, Alan Bates and Irene Papas. It appears that for me events in a movie whiz by before my critical sense can take hold and I enjoy things that I would not on the printed page.<br /><br />Download the film whenever you are in a food for good acting and charming Cretan peasants dancing the syrtaki. <br /><br />Do not read this book. Instead watch a few instructional videos on Greek dancing on YouTube. Then invite your friends offer for a barbecue. Serve chicken skewers and dolmades. Make sure to offer your friends plenty of Retsina and dance away on the lawn until the police arrive. This is my never fail formula for a good time on a summer evening in Toronto. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9806400529626154554" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


